###PORTS
Well Known Ports:
Port      Service          Protocol  
21         FTP          File transfer
22         SSH          Secure remote login
23        Telnet        Unsecure remote login
25         SMTP          Sending email
53         DNS           Domain name lookup
80        HTTP           Web traffic
443       HTTPS         Secure web traffic
3306      MySQL          Database
8080      HTTP         altDev web servers

PORT RANGES
0    - 1023   → System/well-known ports (need root)
1024 - 49151  → Registered ports (applications)
49152 - 65535 → Dynamic/private ports (temporary)

###Curl 
Transfer Data From Servers -it fetches web content from the terminal.
curl [flags] [URL]
Common flags:
Flag      Meaning                                  Example
-v       verbose, show full connection details   curl -v google.com
-I       fetch headers only                       curl -I google.com
-L        follow redirects                        curl -L google.com #usually used when url has been changed and redirects, instead of break, it goes. 
-o      save output to file                       curl -o page.html google.com
-O      save with original filename               curl -O example.com/file.zip
-u      username:password auth                    curl -u user:pass example.com
-X      specify HTTP method                       curl -X POST example.com
-d      send data (POST body)                     curl -d "name=John" example.com
-H      add custom header                         curl -H "Authorization: Bearer token"
-k      ignore SSL certificate errors             curl -k https://example.com
-s      silent mode, no progress bar              curl -s example.com
---------------
curl example.com # Simple fetch a webpage
curl -O https://example.com/file.zip #Download a file
curl -I https://google.com #See server headers only
curl -X POST -d "username=admin&password=1234" http://example.com/login #Send a POST request with data
curl -Lv https://google.com #Follow redirects verbosely
curl -u admin:password123 http://example.com/api #Pass authentication

###nc (Netcat) — Netcat creates raw TCP/UDP connections
nc [flags] [host] [port]
Common Flags:
Flag           Meaning
-l          listen mode (be the server)
-v          verbose output-pspecify port
-u          use UDP instead of TCP
-z          zero I/O — scan only, don't send data
-w          timeout in seconds
-n          no DNS lookup

nc localhost 30002 # Connect to a server on port 30002 (like Bandit)
nc -l -p 1234 # Listen on a port (you become the server)
nc -zv google.com 80 # Port scan a host
# Send a file
nc -l -p 1234 > received_file.txt      # receiver
nc hostname 1234 < file_to_send.txt    # sender

# Simple chat between two machines
nc -l -p 1234          # machine 1 listens
nc machine1_ip 1234    # machine 2 connects
# now both can type messages to each other

# Banner grabbing (see what service is running)
nc -v example.com 80



